					</div>
				</div>
            <p>Many verbs in modern English have retained this conjugation pattern, for example, 'sing/sang' or 'give/gave'.
                These verbs in modern English are almost all descendants of Old English Strong Verbs. Strong Verbs in the present tense generally follow the same conjugations as for Weak Verbs.
                Compare the following conjugations for the weak verb '<em>hieran</em>' and strong verb '<em>singan</em>' in the present tense.
            </p>
            <div class="row padding-top text-center">
                <table class="static-table table-striped inline-block table-hide">
                    <tr>
                        <td colspan="3">
                            <strong>Present Tense of Hieran and Singan</strong>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <th></th>
                        <th>Hieran</th>
                        <th>Singan</th>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>1st Person Singular</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>Ic hiere</td>
                        <td>Ic singe</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>2nd Person Singular</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>Þu hierst</td>
                        <td>Þu singst</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>3rd Person Singular</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>He/heo/hit hierþ</td>
                        <td>He/Heo/Hit singþ</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>Plural</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>We/Ge/Hie hieraþ</td>
                        <td>We/Ge/Hie singaþ</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>
            <p class="padding-top">As you can see, the endings are the same in the present tense. The table below shows the same two verbs, but this time in the past tense. Notice the vowel change in the root and the ending of the 2nd singular and plural of <em>singan</em>.</p>
            <div class="row padding-top text-center">
                <table class="static-table table-striped inline-block table-hide">
                    <tr>
                        <td colspan="3">
                            <strong>Past Tense of Hieran and Singan</strong>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <th></th>
                        <th>Hierde</th>
                        <th>Singan</th>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>1st Person Singular</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>Ic hiere</td>
                        <td>Ic sang</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>2nd Person Singular</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>Þu hierst</td>
                        <td>Þu sunge</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>3rd Person Singular</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>He/heo/hit hierþ</td>
                        <td>He/heo/hit sang</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <strong>Plural</strong>
                        </td>
                        <td>We/ge/hie hieraþ</td>
                        <td>We/ge/hie sungon</td>
                        
                    </tr>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>
            <p class="padding-top">
                Verbs which follow the same pattern of vowel changes as singan are grouped in the same class of Strong Verbs. In Old English, there are seven classes of strong verb, each identifiable by regular changes to vowels in the root verb,
                and each with its own conjugation pattern. Some of these patterns like 'sing/sang/sung' have survived into modern English
                but some of them can be harder to recognise, so let's explore Strong Verbs class by class.
            </p>
